Now it is time to create your first {@link docularconfigure/sections documentation section}!

Suppose in our "Front End Code" group we want to add documentation for some global utilities functions that live in "javascript/lib/utilities.js". It makes sense to put global utilities into their own section, so let's add a "Global Utilities" section to our group in the Gruntfile.js file configuration and add the scripts we want scanned for documentation.

```js
module.exports = function(grunt) {

    // Project configuration
    grunt.initConfig({

        pkg: grunt.file.readJSON('package.json'),

        docular: {
            groups: [
                {
                    groupTitle: 'Front End Code',
                    groupId: 'frontend',
                    groupIcon: 'icon-beer',
                    sections: [
                        {
                            id: "utilities",
                            title: "Global Utilities",
                            scripts: [
                                "javscript/lib/utilities.js"
                            ],
                            docs: [],
                            rank : {}
                        },
                    ]
                }
            ],
            //other configurations ommitted here for simplicity
        }

    });

    // Load the plugin that provides the "docular" tasks.
    grunt.loadNpmTasks('grunt-docular');

    // Default task(s).
    grunt.registerTask('default', ['docular']);

};
```

<div class="alert">WARNING: Make sure you understand the {@link docularconfigure/sections#docsnscripts difference between scripts and docs}</div>

